Graphical abstract Single-step and two-steps synthetic procedure for the synthesis of sulfated zirconia (SZ) was developed, which were calcined at 500, 600 and 700°C and characterized by various physico-chemical methods such as PXRD, FTIR, surface area, microanalysis, NH3-TPD and DRIFT analysis. These SZ materials were then employed as solid acid catalysts for the aminolysis of different aliphatic/aromatic terminal, aryloxy and meso epoxides with aromatic and aliphatic amines under ambient conditions. Amongst the catalyst prepared, SZ-2-600 prepared in two-steps and 600°C calcined was found to be the most efficient catalyst to give β-amino alcohols in up to 98% yield and >99% regioselectivity. The SZ catalyst was successfully recycled and reused up to six catalytic runs with intact efficiency. Keywords Sulfated zirconia Aminolysis of epoxide Solid acid catalyst β-Amino alcohols Aryloxy and aliphatic epoxides 1 Introduction Aminolysis of epoxide (AoE) is one among the most atom efficient methods to produce racemic and non-racemic β-amino alcohols, which are commonly found in natural and synthetic molecules of commercial importance [1–6]. A real issue with AoE is regioselectivity, as either carbon of a non-symmetric epoxide can react with the nucleophile to produce regioisomers (Fig. 1 ). Plenty of literature is available on AoE that include non-catalytic [7–10] and catalytic approaches [5,6,11–43] with moderate to high success. Noticeable results in AoE were achieved with Brønsted [11–15] and Lewis acids [16–21] under homogeneous condition and with solid acid materials [21–42] under heterogeneous condition with moderate to excellent yield and selectivity of β-amino alcohols. A closer look into the structure of β-amino alcohol of commercial importance would reveal that structural variations (substituents) on motifs (Fig. 1) originating from epoxide as well as amine are prevalent. Therefore, a catalyst which can perform AoE effectively for variety of aliphatic and aryloxy epoxides with variety of aromatic and aliphatic amines is highly desirable and such efforts have been reported in the past with mixed success [5,6,9,14,18–21]. Here we report, synthesis of nano-sized sulfated zirconia (SZ) [40–51] having super acidity/high acid strength, hydrothermal stability as solid acid catalyst for AoE. As such SZ is a well-known solid acid catalyst for various commercially important organic transformations [40–47]. In fact SZ has been used in the AoE under solvent free condition by Negrón-Silva et al. [40] and under microwave irradiation and by Reddy et al. [41] in high yields but in later case the reaction took longer time. Das et al. [42] efficiently opened the epoxide ring with substituted indoles via CC bond forming reaction using SZ catalyst. Recently, Pathare et al. [6] reported sulfated tungstate as potential solid acid catalyst for AoE of various epoxides with amines. However, in this case, catalyst preparation method required hazardous sulfonation source-ClSO3H, chlorinated organic solvent and subambient reaction temperature (0–5°C). Therefore, still there is a room to improve overall AoE process particularly in exploring wide variety substrate ranges, developing easily synthesizable and recyclable catalysts for commercial applications. It is well known in the literature that catalytic activity of SZ significantly depends upon its texture properties, use of zirconium precursor, sulfating agent, types of preparation method and activating temperature [43–51]. With this backdrop, we present here the synthesis of sulfated zirconia catalyst by single-step and two-steps preparation methods using zirconium n-propoxide (Zr(OC3H7)4) as a source of zirconium and sulfuric acid as a sulfating agent. The resultant zirconia materials were calcined at different temperatures in order to achieve optimum catalytic activity. In single-step method, SZ materials were prepared by sol–gel process of Oh. et al. [46] with some modifications, where initially zirconium precursor was hydrolyzed followed by in situ sulfation of the sol–gel obtained was carried out by the addition of sulfuric acid. The solid obtained was dried at 120°C to give solid sulfated zirconia catalyst henceforth known as SZ-1-120, which was further calcined at 500, 600 and 700°C temperatures giving catalysts SZ-1-500, SZ-1-600 and SZ-1-700 respectively. In two-steps process, the method of Mishra et al. [47] was used, where in first step zirconium hydroxide was prepared by the hydrolysis of (Zr(OC3H7)4) with ammonia followed by sulfation of zirconium hydroxide with sulphuric acid in second step. Drying of the resultant powder at 120°C (SZ-2-120) and subsequent calcination at 500, 600 and 700°C temperatures furnished catalysts SZ-2-500, SZ-2-600 and SZ-2-700 respectively. As synthesized SZ materials were then employed as catalyst in AoE under solvent free condition at RT. Among the SZ materials used, SZ-2-600, prepared in two steps was found to have the best catalytic activity in terms of yield and selectivity of β-amino alcohols in short reaction time under solvent free condition at RT. The catalyst, SZ-2-600 was also found to be effective for a variety of aliphatic cyclic or acyclic, aromatic and aryloxy epoxides with aliphatic/aromatic primary and secondary amines. Since in most of the cases product is either viscous liquid or solid, the catalyst after each catalytic cycle was easily recovered by filtration/centrifugation with an appropriate solvent then dried for reuse. The recovered catalyst showed no signs of loss in its performance even after six catalytic runs studied. 2 Experimental 2.1 Materials and methods X-ray Powder Diffraction studies were carried out using X’pert Mpd, PHILIPS and Empyrean XRD systems from PANanalytical (Japan) within 2θ range of 10–65° using CuKα1 (λ =1.54060Å) at ambient temperature. Surface area and pore size distribution of SZ materials were determined by nitrogen adsorption–desorption method at 77.35K by using ASAP 2020 instrument, Micromeritics Inc., USA. All SZ samples were activated at 393K under vacuum just prior to measurements. FT-IR spectra were recorded on Perkin Elmer Spectrum GX spectrophotometer (USA) using KBr window. JEOL, JEM-2100 microscope (Japan) was used for transmission electron microscopic (TEM) analysis at 200kV using carbon coated copper grid. For this SZ material was dispersed in ethanol and a drop of the dispersion was placed on copper grid to determine the textural properties of the materials. Elemental analysis was done on CHNS analyzer “ElementarVario MICRO Cube (Germany)”. Diffuse Reflectance FT-IR spectroscopy (DRIFT) was used to determine the Brønsted/Lewis (B/L) acid ratio of pyridine adsorpted SZ samples using Perkin Elmer GX equipped with DRIFT Selector accessory (Graseby Specac, P/N 19900 series). The spectra were recorded at room temperature (27°C), 150°C and 250°C after holding at each temperature for 10min, thus allowing sufficient time for pyridine desorption. NMR spectra were recorded on a Bruker F113V spectrometer (200MHz and 500MHz, Switzerland) using TMS as an internal standard. GC analysis was done on GC-2010AF APC instrument (Shimadzu, Japan) using BP-5 capillary column (SGE, USA). The aminolysis products were purified by flash chromatography using silica gel 60–120 and 100–200 mesh purchased from s. d. Fine Chem. Ltd., India. Zirconium n-propoxide and various cyclic, acyclic, aryloxy and meso epoxides, aromatic and aliphatic amines (substituted amines) were purchased from Aldrich chemicals and used as received (USA). 2.2 Synthesis of sulfated zirconia (SZ) catalysts Sulfated zirconia materials were synthesized by using single-step and two-step processes as follows. 2.2.1 Single-step process for the synthesis of SZ catalysts The single-step process [46] was slightly modified wherein Zr(OC3H7)4 (10mL, 70% in n-propanol) was diluted with 12.5mL of n-propanol (up to 30%) to which 1N aqueous solution of H2SO4 (20mL) was added drop-wise under vigorous stirring within 30min and the resultant reaction mixture was stirred for another 6h. The white solid thus obtained was filtered and dried at 120°C (SZ-1-120) followed by calcination at 500, 600 and 700°C for 4h giving catalysts SZ-1-500, SZ-1-600 and SZ-1-700 respectively. 2.2.2 Two-steps synthesis of SZ catalysts In the two-steps process [47], hydrolysis of (Zr(OC3H7)4) (30wt.% solution in n-propanol) was carried out by using aqueous ammonia. At pH 9–10 Zr(OH)4 gel was formed which was dried at 110°C. In the second step, sulfation of Zr(OH)4 dried powder was carried out by using 15mL/g solution of 1N H2SO4. White solid thus obtained was filtered and dried at 120°C (SZ-2-120) overnight and calcined at 500, 600 and 700°C giving catalysts SZ-2-500, SZ-2-600 and SZ-2-700 respectively. 2.2.3 Synthesis of zirconia-ZrO2 For the sake of comparison, unpromoted zirconia-ZrO 2 was prepared by the calcination of zirconium hydroxide at 350°C for 4h. 2.3 Catalytic procedure for aminolysis of epoxide (AoE) using SZ catalyst A solid SZ catalyst (20mg), an epoxide (1mmol) and an amine (1mmol) were taken in a 5mL screw capped vial and stirred magnetically for a given time period (monitored by GC or TLC) under solvent free condition at RT. On completion of the reaction, viscous liquid or solid product obtained was treated with methanol (2×3mL) and centrifuged for the complete removal of organic compounds from the solid catalyst. The evaporation of solvent from the combined organic layers furnished the crude product. A small fraction of the crude product was directly injected to HPLC to find out the regioselectivity. The remaining portion of the crude mixture was purified by flash column chromatography (hexane/ethyl acetate, 80:20) to get the major regioisomer in pure form. The purified product was characterized by 1H and 13C NMR analysis. The residue thus obtained from centrifugation was dried in air (2h) and then at 200°C for 3h to get back the active catalyst (>97% recovery) for the next catalytic run. The characterization data of some ring opening products are given in Supplementary Information. 3 Results and discussion 3.1 Catalyst characterization 3.1.1 Powder X-ray diffraction technique PXRD patterns of different SZ catalysts prepared in single-step and two-steps methods are shown in Fig. 2 (A) and (B), respectively. The SZ catalysts SZ-1-120 and SZ-2-120 (non-calcined) and SZ-1-500 and SZ-2-500 (calcined at 500 and 600°C, respectively) were found to have amorphous nature irrespective of their synthetic methods. SZ catalyst prepared in a single-step and calcined at 600°C (SZ-1-600) showed crystalline metastable tetragonal phase which was transformed into more stable monoclinic phase when calcined at 700°C to give tetragonal and monoclinic mixed phase (28:72) of the catalyst SZ-1-700. Noticeably phase transformation of sulfated zirconia was found to be associated with the loss of impregnated sulfate ions [43–48], as it can be seen in the loss of sulphur in elemental analysis (Table 1 ). SZ catalysts prepared in two steps SZ-2-600 (calcined at 600°C) and SZ-2-700 (calcined at 700°C) showed the crystalline reflections at 2 theta values 30.4, 35.3, 50.4, 59.4, 60.3, 63.0 and 74.7 of pure tetragonal phase (JCPDS no. 88-1007). However, in this case no phase transformation was observed. Crystallite sizes (Table 1) as calculated by applying the Scherrer equation to XRD reflections for catalysts SZ-1-600 and SZ-1-700 were found to be ∼30nm, which were significantly higher than SZ-2-600 and SZ-2-700 (∼7nm). Comparatively, the crystallite size of unpromoted zirconia was of the order of ∼49nm. The size reduction of sulfated zirconia crystals is attributed to the presence of impregnated sulfate ions, which is known to retard the growth of crystallite size in unpromoted zirconia [43,44,48]. 3.1.2 FT-IR studies IR spectra (Fig. 3 ) of SZ samples show broad bands in the range of 990–1220cm−1 confirming the successful impregnation of sulfate ions in the material. All the SZ samples show bands at around 993, 1057, 1130 and 1212cm−1 which are the characteristic peaks of bidented chelation of sulfate ions due to SO and SO bonds [43,44,47,49]. The band appeared at ∼993cm−1 can be attributed to the symmetric (υ1) vibrations of SO bond while 1057, 1130 and 1212cm−1 bands are assigned to asymmetric (υ3) stretching frequencies of OSO bonds [49]. The ionic nature of SO imparts the Brønsted acid site to the SZ which enhance the acidity of the material and thereby reinforcing catalytic activity. A broad peak around 3300cm−1 and an intense peak ∼1630cm−1 are attributed to the stretching and bending vibrations of the water molecules respectively. Due to the large population of sulfate groups in non-calcined sample SZ-1-120 and SZ-2-120 bands in this region were intense and merged to give a broad band. However, the intensity of these peaks decreases on increasing the calcination temperature due to loss of sulfate groups upon calcination which is in good agreement with the TGA analysis and sulfur values obtained by microanalysis (Table 1). 3.1.3 Thermo gravimetric analysis and microanalysis TG plots of all the catalysts demonstrated continuous reduction in % weight loss (Table 1; Fig. S1–S8 in Supplementary Information) from the material on increasing calcination temperature can be attributed to the removal of water adsorbed and decomposition of sulfate groups from the SZ materials. Non-calcined samples demonstrated higher initial weight loss between 100°C and 250°C due to desorption of water. Broadness in the graph at around 400°C was possibly due to the removal of water and oxygen from sulfate groups indicating the presence of strong acidic sites [51]. Finally, a sharp weight loss observed at >550°C temperature due to the removal of sulfate groups except for samples SZ-1-700 and SZ-2-700. Eventually, sulfur values of all the samples were evaluated by microanalysis (Table 1), which showed same trend of continuous decrease in sulphur content on increasing the calcination temperature consistent with TG analysis. 3.1.4 N2 adsorption–desorption isotherm studies The results from the N2 adsorption–desorption isotherm study of SZ catalysts carried out at 77K are summarized in Table 1. Amorphous SZ-1-120, SZ-1-500, SZ-2-120 and SZ-2-500 catalysts exhibited type-III hysteresis loop in the range P/P o =0.4–0.5 confirming the macroporous structure of the material (entries 2, 3, 6, 7). Moreover, these materials possess very low BET surface area ∼10m2/g but high pore volumes (0.1–0.2cc/g) possibly due to the presence of large pores, which are populated with sulfate groups, thereby filling the pores of material except in the case sample SZ-2-120-a typical characteristics for the samples bearing intra-particular porosity. The crystalline SZ-1-600, SZ-1-700, SZ-2-600 and SZ-2-700 (entries 4, 5, 8, 9) materials showed the type-IV hysteresis loop in the range P/P o =0.4–0.5 suggesting the mesoporous structure of these materials. Catalyst SZ-2-120 to SZ-2-700 materials show continuous reduction in total surface area from 103 to 57m2/g on increasing the calcination temperature, but no such trend was seen in the case of SZ-1-120 to SZ-1-700 materials. 3.1.5 Ammonia-temperature programmed desorption (NH3-TPD) technique The strength and concentration of Brønsted or Lewis acidic sites of SZ catalysts were determined by NH3-TPD technique to get an idea about types of acidic sites in SZ material (Fig. 4 (A) and (B) and Table 2 ). TPD graphs of catalysts prepared in single-step (Fig. 4 (A)) showed predominantly two types of the acidic sites; Lewis acidic sites at ∼100°C as in SZ-1-600 and SZ-1-700 [44,49–51] and strong Brønsted acidic sites at 650–750°C as in SZ-1-500 and SZ-1-600. Brønsted acid sites in SZ-1-500 showed unexpectedly intense peak in this region suggesting the presence of large amount of sulfate groups on the surface. This peak marginally reduced when the calcination temperature was raised from 500 to 600°C (SZ-1-600) and nearly disappears at 700°C (SZ-1-700) indicating the removal of sulfate ions coupled with phase transformation process as is evident in PXRD patterns. Further, SZ-1-500 showed highest amount of total acidic sites (3.22mmol of NH3/g, Table 2), which reduces significantly to 0.5–0.2mmol of NH3/g on increasing the calcination temperature (SZ-1-600 and SZ-1-700; Table 2). Catalysts prepared in two-steps showed markedly different TCD profile. Samples SZ-2-600 and SZ-2-700 (Fig. 4 (B)) showed weak acidic sites at ∼100°C, and moderate Lewis and Brønsted acidic sites in the range of 200–500°C [44,51]. These peaks gradually diminished in catalysts SZ-2-500 to SZ-2-700 due to continuous loss of sulfate ions upon calcination. Strong NH3-desorption peaks observed at >500°C indicate the presence of strong Brønsted acidic sites of sulfate ions which in turn enhances total acidity of catalyst and catalytic activity. Both the catalysts prepared by single-step and two-steps processes showed similar trend in acid strengths when subjected to calcination at different temperatures, similar results were also observed by Marakatti et al. [50]. Moreover, total numbers of acid sites in SZ-2-500 (1.05g/mmol) are fewer than SZ-2-600 (1.50g/mmol) but more than SZ-2-700 (0.55g/mmol) because in former, the presence of surface sulfate groups (Brønsted acid site) tend to masks the Lewis acid sites of the solid [44]. The increase in total acidity from SZ-2-500 to SZ-2-600 is possibly due to the removal of some amount of sulfate ions and thereby opening the face of Lewis acid sites inside the pores and on external solid surface. The deconvoluted TPD graph of SZ-2-600 clearly shows distribution of weak to moderate acidic sites in the temperature range of 200–550°C (Fig. S9, see Supplementary Information). 3.1.6 DRIFT analysis The DRIFT spectra of pyridine adsorbed SZ samples prepared in two steps (SZ-2-500, SZ-2-600, SZ-2-700) showed characteristic bands at 1540 and 1612cm−1 corresponding to Brønsted acid sites while band at 1441cm−1 corresponding to Lewis acidic sites (Fig. 5 ) [49]. The peak area and B/L ratio (see Table S1, Supporting Information) exhibited similar trend as seen in NH3-TPD experiments where initially this parameter increases from samples SZ-2-500 to SZ-2-600 but decreased for SZ-2-700 suggesting that the Lewis acid character increases with decrease in Brønsted acid character. 3.2 Catalytic studies of SZ catalysts for AoE reaction 3.2.1 Optimization of the catalysts and its loading The catalysis results of SZ catalyst AoE reaction using cyclohexenoxide and aniline as model substrates at 1mmol scale are summarized in Table 3 . Zirconia and zirconium hydroxide (20mg) gave moderate yields of β-amino alcohol in 72 and 80% respectively under solvent free condition at room temperature in 60min (entries 1, 2) indicating that the Brønsted acidity of the catalyst enhances the yield of AoE reaction. While sulfate group incorporated SZ-1-120 and SZ-1-500 catalysts increases product yield up to 85% (entries 3, 4) within 30min showing the influence of acid strength of the sulfated catalyst. However, catalysts SZ-1-600 and SZ-1-700 improved the yield of β-amino alcohol to 93 and 90% respectively (entries 5, 6) indicating that acidity and surface area of the SZ catalysts are the driving factors for AoE reactions. Even though the catalyst SZ-1-600 showed excellent activity initially, its activity dropped substantially on subsequent catalytic runs mainly due to the loss of sulphate ions as was evident from the loss of sulphur content in the recycled catalyst. When non-calcined SZ-2-120 and calcined SZ-2-500 catalysts were used, an enhancement in yield 87% and 92% (entries 7, 8) was observed as compared to catalysts SZ-1-120 and SZ-1-500, possibly due to higher surface area of the catalysts prepared in two-steps. Moreover, when SZ-2-600 catalyst used, a significant improvement in the product yield (96%, entry 9) was achieved, which was higher than the yield obtained with SZ-2-700 catalyst (90%, entry 10) within 30min. It is noteworthy that no regioisomer was observed in 1H NMR in any of these cases. It is evident from the above results that the catalyst SZ-2-600 is most efficient in terms of activity and selectivity for AoE reaction. In order to find optimal catalyst loading, 15, 25 and 35mg of catalyst SZ-2-600 per 1mmol of substrate were tested (entries 11–13). There was no lowering in the selectivity at 25 and 35mg catalyst loading, but there was a drop in overall yield of the product at higher catalyst loading possibly due to stirring issues in the heterogeneous system. However, 20mg catalyst per 1mmol of substrate was found to be the best to achieve the highest catalytic activity for AoE reaction. 3.2.2 Scope of various substrates for AoE reaction under optimized reaction condition Above optimum reaction condition was then applied to aminolysis of various epoxides with different amines using SZ-2-600 catalyst in 60min. Interestingly, epoxide ring fused with five to eight membered cycloalkanes gave a decreasing trend in the activity in AoE with the increase in the ring size of cycloalkane from yield; 98–89%; (Table 4 , entries 1–3), but cyclooctenoxide (entry 4) failed to react with aniline possibly due to increasing steric repulsion caused by hydrophobic methylene groups of cycloalkanes, which is higher in the case of cyclooctenoxide molecule, thus resisting to the attack of nucleophile. In the case of aminolysis of cyclohexenoxide with different substituted anilines, electron releasing groups such as methyl, ethyl, methoxy and chloro at different substituent positions on aromatic ring (entries 5–10) furnished moderate to excellent yield (85–94%) of β-amino alcohols in 60min. However, highly electron withdrawing nitro group on aromatic ring, e.g. 4-nitroaniline fails to open the epoxide ring (entry 11). This protocol was also found to be effective for the aminolysis of internal and terminal aliphatic epoxides. Aminolysis of cis-butenoxide (entry 12) with aniline was found to be more feasible than trans-butenoxide (entry 13) under the similar reaction condition possibly, as stated earlier, due to the steric reasons. Aminolysis of 2-methylpropenoxide with aniline gave 88% yield of amino alcohol within 45min (entry 14). The catalyst SZ-2-600 was also very active for AoE of terminal aliphatic epoxides having carbon chain C4, C6, C8, C10, C12 and C18 with aniline giving excellent yields of the respective ring opened products (90–96%, entries 15–20) within short reaction time. Aliphatic glycidyl ethers such as tertiarybutylglycidyl ether and isopropylglycidyl ether also furnished good product yield (∼90%) within 30min (entries 21–22). Epichlorohydrine (entry 23) and epibromohydrine (entry 24) show almost full conversion when reacted with aniline but gave lower yield of amino alcohol because of the formation of chloro or bromo substituted products. Various aromatic glycidyl ethers were also tested for AoE reaction with anilines where in phenylglycidyl ether (PGE) yielded 90% of β-amino alcohol (entry 25). While 4-tertiarybutyl PGE and 4-chloro PGE gave products in quantitative yields (entries 26–27). 4-Methoxy PGE (entry 28) and 2-methyl PGE (entry 29) afforded 90% yield of the corresponding β-amino alcohols in 30min using catalyst SZ-2-600. The efficacy of this catalyst was then screened for aminolysis of PGE with aliphatic amines. AoE reaction of PGE with branched aliphatic amine-isopropyl amine was relatively less regioselective (yield 82%, entry 30) than its linear version n-propyl amine where only one regioisomer formed (yield 95%, entry 31). Secondary amines with long alkyl chain e.g. in dioctlyamine gave epoxide ring opened product only in moderate yield (68%, entry 32) possible due to higher hydrophobicity and steric constraints. SZ-2-600 catalyst was also found to be effective in AoE reaction of PGE with heterocyclic amines such as piperidine and morpholine achieving excellent 94 and 97% yield of β-amino alcohol respectively (entries 33-34). The synthesis of couple of drug molecules such as (S)-Propranolol and (S)-Naftopidil via SZ-2-600 catalyzed aminolysis of (S)-naphthylglycidyl ether with isopropyl amine and 1-(2-methoxyphenyl)piperazine was achieved in 85 and 88% yield respectively (entries 35–36) under solvent free condition with complete retention of configuration suggesting that the present protocol does not trigger racemization of chiral epoxide. However, in the case of (S)-Propranolol regioselectivity was found to be 90:10 which needs to be addressed for making this process commercially more acceptable. Ironically for the reasons not know at this point of time, SZ-2-600 failed to catalyze ring opening reaction of cis-stilbene oxide with aniline at RT and even at 60°C (entry 37). From above results it can be clearly stated that the catalyst SZ-2-600 with highly crystalline tetragonal phase, large surface area, super acidic strength and nano-scale size prepared via two-steps processes and calcined at 600°C is optimum for the aminolysis of wide range of epoxide with various amines. 3.2.3 Recycling of catalyst SZ-2-600 for AoE reaction under optimized reaction condition Recyclability and reusability of SZ-2-600 for AoE reaction of cyclohexenoxide with aniline was checked up to six catalytic runs in which the catalyst showed its intact efficiency in terms of activity and selectivity as shown in Fig. 6 . However, to get the consistent results from the used catalyst, it was washed with methanol to remove any trapped product and starting materials and then activated at 200°C for 3h essentially to remove solvent molecules trapped inside the pores of the catalyst before it was used for next catalytic run. The used catalyst after sixth use experiment was characterized by physico-chemical methods that showed similar characteristics shown by the fresh catalyst. 4 Conclusions Various grades of sulfated zirconia were prepared via single-step and two-steps processes and calcined at different temperatures. Out of these SZ-2-600, synthesized in two-steps process and calcined at 600°C was found to be the most active acid catalyst in the aminolysis of a wide range of epoxides with various aliphatic and aromatic amines under solvent free condition at RT. Parameters like highly crystalline and stable tetragonal phase, large surface area, strength and higher fraction of super acidic sites and nano-scale of the catalyst are main driving factors for high catalytic activity of SZ-2-600 catalyst. The SZ catalyst was also found to be active for comparatively less reactive aliphatic terminal and meso-epoxides with amines providing desired products in excellent yield and selectivity. The SZ catalyst was successfully recycled for six catalytic cycles without any significant loss in its activity. Acknowledgements CSIR-CSMCRI communication no. is DIMC-015-14. coredata.dc:description: Single-step and two-steps synthetic procedure for the synthesis of sulfated zirconia (SZ) was developed, which were calcined at 500, 600 and 700°C and characterized by various physico-chemical methods such as PXRD, FTIR, surface area, microanalysis, NH3-TPD and DRIFT analysis. These SZ materials were then employed as solid acid catalysts for the aminolysis of different aliphatic/aromatic terminal, aryloxy and meso epoxides with aromatic and aliphatic amines under ambient conditions. Amongst the catalyst prepared, SZ-2-600 prepared in two-steps and 600°C calcined was found to be the most efficient catalyst to give β-amino alcohols in up to 98% yield and >99% regioselectivity. The SZ catalyst was successfully recycled and reused up to six catalytic runs with intact efficiency.
coredata.dc:title: Solvent-free aminolysis of aliphatic and aryloxy epoxides with sulfated zirconia as solid acid catalyst
